%N A394258 Largest prime less than the n-th prime-complete number.
%C A394258 An integer is designated "prime-complete" if and only if it has at least one prime divisor and its prime divisors form a complete contiguous set from 2 to its greatest prime divisor. Equivalently, n is prime-complete iff its distinct prime factors are exactly {2, 3, ..., prime(k)} for some k >= 1. The sequence A055932 comprises all the prime-complete numbers together with the number 1. The number, 4, is the second prime-complete number, so a(2) = 3.
%C A394258 A double (two prime-complete numbers in one prime gap) occurs only for the shared previous-primes 31, 89, 479, and 4603; no further double exists below 10^12, and a heuristic based on the density of prime-complete numbers suggests this list of doubles is complete and that no triple occurs. That is, the counting function for prime-complete numbers, A377028(n), grows sub-polynomially (empirically exp(O(sqrt(log n)))), so prime-complete numbers thin out faster than any polynomial while prime gaps grow only logarithmically. The expected number of further doubles beyond x is therefore a convergent sum, supporting the conjecture that the complete list is 31, 89, 479, and 4603.
%C A394258 For large numbers the average gap from a prime-complete number to the previous prime grows on the same order as prime gaps, approximately log(n). The largest gap from a prime-complete number to the previous prime, for numbers less than 10^12, is 313 at n = 238133575680 (2^17*3*5*7*11^3*13) following the prime number 238133575367.
%H A394258 Ken Clements, <a href="/A394258/b394258.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%F A394258 a(n) = A151799(A055932(n+1)).
%o A394258 (Python)
%o A394258 from sympy import prime, primefactors, prevprime
%o A394258 SEARCH_GOAL = 120 # Find this many terms
%o A394258 def is_prime_complete(n):
%o A394258    pf = primefactors(n)
%o A394258    return prime(len(pf)) == pf[-1]
%o A394258 last_prime_complete, results = 4, []
%o A394258 while len(results) < SEARCH_GOAL:
%o A394258    results.append(prevprime(last_prime_complete))
%o A394258    last_prime_complete += 2
%o A394258    while not is_prime_complete(last_prime_complete): last_prime_complete += 2
%o A394258 print(results)
%Y A394258 Cf. A055932, A151799, A377028, A396087.
%K A394258 nonn,new
%O A394258 2,1
%A A394258 _Ken Clements_, May 27 2026
